{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2187829b-3295-4efd-aaf0-97d51fcd50e0","content":"Here's a quick diagnostic approach for a hung .NET 8 app on Linux:\n\n**1. Identify the process:**\n```bash\nps aux | grep dotnet\n# or\npidof YourAppName\n```\n\n**2. Capture a thread dump (non-destructive):**\n```bash\n# Using dotnet-dump or kill -3\ndotnet-dump collect -p <PID>\ndotnet-dump analyze <dump-file>\n> clrthreads\n> dumpasync\n```\n\n**3. Quick live check with `dotnet-stack`:**\n```bash\ndotnet-stack report -p <PID>\n```\nThis shows what every thread is doing — look for threads stuck in locks, I/O waits, or deadlocks.\n\n**4. Check for threadpool starvation:**\n```bash\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nWatch `ThreadPool Queue Length` and `ThreadPool Thread Count`.\n\n**5. If tools aren't installed:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-stack\n```\n\n**Common culprits:**\n- **Deadlock** — `dumpasync` in the dump will show async methods awaiting each other\n- **ThreadPool starvation** — sync-over-async (`.Result`/`.Wait()`) blocking all pool threads\n- **GC suspension** — check `% Time in GC` via `dotnet-counters`\n- **Waiting on external resource** — DB, HTTP call with no timeout\n\nWould you like help interpreting specific output from any of these tools?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5f23623d-c651-434a-8c80-dba57a9e82e2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for help diagnosing a hung .NET 8 application on a Linux VM. This is a troubleshooting/diagnostic question rather than a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance on how to diagnose a hung .NET application on Linux.","outputTokens":466,"requestId":"5021:35C209:1F17EC9:237DB30:69F550FF"},"id":"3a1a28a8-3123-4e0e-b2f1-486746b8503e","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:19:06.292Z","parentId":"6238f8e7-115d-4371-920d-c9d57fc3d429"}
